elements.title: Taraxacum britannicum
elements.contents: ... that although Taraxacum britannicum (pictured) is commonly called the British dandelion, specimens have been collected as far north as Iceland?

elements.title: Asri Rasad
elements.contents: ... that former University of Indonesia dean Asri Rasad used to work as a liaison officer for the Indonesian Army to the Allied Forces headquarters?

elements.title: Rephaim text
elements.contents: ... that the Rephaim text, a 14th-century BCE Ugaritic poem, tells of mysterious warrior beings who ride for three days to a threshing floor – only to spend the next seven days eating there?

elements.title: Warren Kilbourne
elements.contents: ... that Warren Kilbourne led a strike against a professional football team because he was not paid for participation in a charity game?

elements.title: a train station in Singapore
elements.contents: ... that a train station in Singapore features an artwork with different types of chairs in a family tree?

elements.title: The Rector of Justin
elements.contents: ... that the choice between The Rector of Justin and Herzog for the 1965 National Book Award for Fiction was described as "a conflict of philosophies" about life itself?

elements.title: Charlie Suff
elements.contents: ... that Charlie Suff is the third actor to portray Johnny Carter on the soap opera EastEnders?

elements.title: a peasant rebellion
elements.contents: ... that the "monstrous" behavior of landlord Han Kik Ko led to a peasant rebellion, in which he was killed?

elements.title: William Longsword
elements.contents: ... that the knight William Longsword was expected to succeed his sickly brother-in-law King Baldwin IV, but succumbed to an illness that the king survived?
